       </p>
    </answer>
</example>
</introduction>

<subsection xml:id="Subsection-General-and-Particular-Solutions">
    <title>General and Particular Solutions</title>


<definition xml:id="def-asshomsys">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Given any linear system <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}</m>, the system <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{0}</m> is called the <term>associated homogeneous system</term>.
        </p>
    </statement>
</definition>

<p>
It turns out that there is a relationship between solutions of <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}</m> and solutions of the associated homogeneous system.
</p>


<exploration xml:id="init-generalplusparticular">
    <p>
        Let 
<me>
    A=\begin{bmatrix}1\amp 2\amp 4\\3\amp -7\amp -1\\-1\amp 4\amp 2\end{bmatrix}\quad\text{and}\quad\mathbf{b}=\begin{bmatrix}-2\\7\\-4\end{bmatrix}
</me>

Consider the matrix equation <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}</m>.  Row reduction produces the following.

<me>
    \left[\begin{array}{ccc|c}  
 1\amp 2\amp 4\amp -2\\3\amp -7\amp -1\amp 7\\-1\amp 4\amp 2\amp -4
 \end{array}\right]\begin{array}{c}
 \\
 \rightsquigarrow\\
 \\
 \end{array}\left[\begin{array}{ccc|c}  
 1\amp 0\amp 2\amp 0\\0\amp 1\amp 1\amp -1\\0\amp 0\amp 0\amp 0
 \end{array}\right]
</me>

 We conclude that <m>\mathbf{x}=\begin{bmatrix}-2t\\-1-t\\t\end{bmatrix}</m>.  
</p>

 <problem>
<statement>
    <p>
Let's take a more careful look at <m>\mathbf{x}</m>. Rewrite
<me>
    \mathbf{x}=\begin{bmatrix}-2t\\-1-t\\t\end{bmatrix}    
</me>

onto its parametric form.
    </p>
</statement>
 
<answer>
    <p>
<me>
    \mathbf{x}=\begin{bmatrix}-2t\\-1-t\\t\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}0\\-1\\0\end{bmatrix}+\begin{bmatrix}-2\\-1\\1\end{bmatrix}t.
    
</me>
</p>
</answer>
</problem>


<p>
 We now see that the solution vector <m>\mathbf{x}</m> is made up of two distinct parts: 
 <ul>
 <li>
      <p> one specific vector <m>\begin{bmatrix}0\\-1\\0\end{bmatrix}</m> </p>
</li>
 <li>
      <p> infinitely many scalar multiples of <m>\begin{bmatrix}-2\\-1\\1\end{bmatrix}</m>.   </p>
</li>
 </ul>
</p>

<p>
 The vector <m>\begin{bmatrix}0\\-1\\0\end{bmatrix}</m> is an example of a <term>particular solution</term>.  
 This particular ``particular solution" corresponds to <m>t=0</m>.  We can find any number of particular solutions by letting <m>t</m> assume different values.  
 For example, the particular solution that corresponds to <m>t=1</m> is <m>\begin{bmatrix}-2\\-2\\1\end{bmatrix}</m>.  
 Let <m>\mathbf{x}_p</m> be any particular solution of <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}</m>.  It turns out that all vectors of the form 
<me>
    \mathbf{x}=\mathbf{x}_p+\begin{bmatrix}-2\\-1\\1\end{bmatrix}t
</me>
 are solutions of <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}</m>.  We can verify this as follows
 
<md>
<mrow>   A\mathbf{x} \amp =A\left(\mathbf{x}_p+\begin{bmatrix}-2\\-1\\1\end{bmatrix}t\right) </mrow> 
<mrow>   \amp =A\mathbf{x}_p+\begin{bmatrix}1\amp 2\amp 4\\3\amp -7\amp -1\\-1\amp 4\amp 2\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}-2\\-1\\1\end{bmatrix}t </mrow> 
<mrow>   \amp =A\mathbf{x}_p+\mathbf{0}=\mathbf{b}. </mrow>
</md>

 This shows that the specific vector <m>\begin{bmatrix}0\\-1\\0\end{bmatrix}</m> is not very special, as any solution of <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}</m> can be used in its place.  
 
 The vector <m>\begin{bmatrix}-2\\-1\\1\end{bmatrix}</m>, however, is special.  
 Note that
 
<me>
    A\begin{bmatrix}-2\\-1\\1\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}1\amp 2\amp 4\\3\amp -7\amp -1\\-1\amp 4\amp 2\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}-2\\-1\\1\end{bmatrix}=\mathbf{0}.
</me>

 So <m>\begin{bmatrix}-2\\-1\\1\end{bmatrix}</m> and all of its scalar multiples are solutions to the associated homogeneous system.
    </p>
</exploration>






<observation>
    <statement>
    <p>
In <xref ref="init-generalplusparticular"/> we found that the general solution of the equation <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}</m> has the form:

<me>
    \mathbf{x}=(\text{Any Particular Solution of}\,A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}) + (\text{General Solution of}\,A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{0}).
</me>

It turns out that the general solution of any linear system can be written in this format.  <xref ref="th-homogeneous"/> formalizes this result.
</p>
</statement>
</observation>




<theorem xml:id="th-homogeneous">

    <statement>
        <p>
            Suppose <m>\mathbf{x}_p</m> is a particular solution of <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}</m>.
  <ol>
  <li xml:id="item-homogeneous1">
  <p> If <m>\mathbf{x}_h</m> is a solution of the associated homogeneous system, then <m>\mathbf{x}_p+\mathbf{x}_h</m> is a solution of <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}</m>.  </p>
</li>
  <li xml:id="item-homogeneous2">
  <p> If <m>\mathbf{x}_1</m> is a solution of <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}</m>, then there exists a solution of the associated homogeneous system, <m>\mathbf{x}_h</m>, such that  <m>\mathbf{x}_1=\mathbf{x}_p+\mathbf{x}_h</m>. </p>
</li>
  </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>


<proof>
<p>
    We will prove part <xref ref="item-homogeneous2"/>. The proof of part <xref ref="item-homogeneous1"/> is left to the reader.
</p>

<p>[Proof of <xref ref="item-homogeneous2"/>]: Let <m>\mathbf{x}_h=\mathbf{x}_1-\mathbf{x}_p</m>, then 

<me>
    A\mathbf{x}_h=A(\mathbf{x}_1-\mathbf{x}_p)=A\mathbf{x}_1-A\mathbf{x}_p=\mathbf{b}-\mathbf{b}=\mathbf{0}
</me>

and

<me>
    \mathbf{x}_1=\mathbf{x}_p+\mathbf{x}_h
</me>

    </p>
</proof>
</theorem>







<example xml:id="ex-sumofhomandpart">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let 
<me>
    A=\begin{bmatrix}2\amp -4\amp -2\\1\amp -2\amp -1\end{bmatrix}\quad\text{and}\quad \mathbf{b}=\begin{bmatrix}8\\4\end{bmatrix}.
</me>

If possible, find a solution of <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}</m> and express it as a sum of a particular solution and the general solution of the associated homogeneous system. (<m>\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{x}_p+\mathbf{x}_h</m>)
       </p>
    </statement>


    <answer>
        <p>
            First, we obtain the reduced row echelon form

<me>
    \left[\begin{array}{ccc|c}  
 2\amp -4\amp -2\amp 8\\1\amp -2\amp -1\amp 4
 \end{array}\right]\begin{array}{c}
 \\
 \rightsquigarrow\\
 \\
 \end{array}\left[\begin{array}{ccc|c}  
 1\amp -2\amp -1\amp 4\\0\amp 0\amp 0\amp 0
 \end{array}\right].
</me>

 
 So 
<me>
    \mathbf{x}=\begin{bmatrix}4+2s+t\\s\\t\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}4\\0\\0\end{bmatrix}+\begin{bmatrix}2\\1\\0\end{bmatrix}s+\begin{bmatrix}1\\0\\1\end{bmatrix}t
</me>

 In this case 
<me>
    \mathbf{x}_p=\begin{bmatrix}4\\0\\0\end{bmatrix} \quad \ \text{and} \ \quad  \mathbf{x}_h=\begin{bmatrix}2\\1\\0\end{bmatrix}s+\begin{bmatrix}1\\0\\1\end{bmatrix}t
</me>
       </p>
    </answer>
</example>
</subsection>







    <subsection xml:id="Subsection-Linear-Independence">
        <title>Linear Independence</title>

        <p>
            Homogeneous linear systems allow us to define a very important concept: <term>linear independence</term>.
        </p>

        <definition xml:id="def-linearindependence">
            <title>Linear Independence</title>

            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let <m>\mathbf{v}_1, \mathbf{v}_2,\ldots ,\mathbf{v}_k</m> be vectors of <m>\R^n</m>.
                    We say that the set <m>\{\mathbf{v}_1, \mathbf{v}_2,\ldots ,\mathbf{v}_k\}</m> is <term>linearly independent</term> 
                    if the only solution to the homogeneous linear combination equation 
                    <men xml:id="eq-defLinInd">
                        c_1\mathbf{v}_1+c_2\mathbf{v}_2+\ldots +c_k\mathbf{v}_k=\mathbf{0}
                    </men>
                    is the <term>trivial solution</term> <m>c_1=c_2=\ldots =c_k=0</m>.
                </p> 

                <p> 
                    If, in addition to the trivial solution, a <term>non-trivial solution</term> (not all <m>c_1, c_2,\ldots ,c_k</m> are zero) 
                    exists, then the set <m>\{\mathbf{v}_1, \mathbf{v}_2,\ldots ,\mathbf{v}_k\}</m> is called <term>linearly dependent</term>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>

        <remark xml:id="LinIndEquiv">
            <p>
                Given a set of vectors <m>X=\{\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots,\mathbf{v}_k\}</m> we can now ask the following questions:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Are the vectors in <m>X</m> linearly dependent according to <xref ref="def-linearindependence"/>? 
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                             Can we write one element of <m>X</m> as a linear combination of the others? 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                It turns out that these questions are equivalent.  In other words, if the answer to one of them 
                is ``YES", the answer to the other is also ``YES".  
                Conversely, if the answer to one of them is ``NO", then the answer to the other is also ``NO".  
                We will start by illustrating this idea with an example, then conclude this section by formally 
                proving the equivalency.
            </p>
        </remark>

        <example xml:id="ex-linind">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    What can we say about the following sets of vectors in light of Remark <xref ref="LinIndEquiv"/>?
                    <ol>
                        <li xml:id="item-linindpart1">
                            <p>
                                <me>
                                    \begin{bmatrix}2\\-3\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}0\\3\end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}1\\-1\end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}1\\-2\end{bmatrix}.
                                </me>
                            </p>
                        </li>


                        <li xml:id="item-linindpart2">
                            <p>
                                <me>
                                    \begin{bmatrix}2\\1\\4\end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}-3\\1\\1\end{bmatrix}.
                                </me>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    We will start by addressing linear independence for <xref ref="item-linindpart1"/>.  To do so, we will solve the linear combination equation
                    <men xml:id="linrelationpart1">
                        c_1 \begin{bmatrix} 2\\-3 \end{bmatrix} 
                            + c_2 \begin{bmatrix}0\\3\end{bmatrix}
                            + c_3\begin{bmatrix}1\\-1\end{bmatrix}
                            + c_4\begin{bmatrix}1\\-2\end{bmatrix}
                            = \mathbf{0}.
                    </men>
                    Clearly <m>c_1=c_2=c_3=c_4=0</m> is a solution to the equation.  The question is whether another solution exists.
                    The linear combination equation translates into the following system:
                    <me>
                        \begin{array}{ccccccccc}
                            2c_1 \amp  \amp \amp +\amp c_3\amp +\amp c_4\amp = \amp 0 \\
                            -3c_1\amp  +\amp 3c_2\amp -\amp c_3\amp -\amp 2c_4\amp = \amp 0 \\
                        \end{array}.
                    </me>
                        Writing the system in augmented matrix form and applying elementary row operations gives us the following reduced row echelon form:
                    <me>
                        \left[\begin{array}{cccc|c}  
                            2\amp 0\amp 1\amp 1\amp 0\\-3\amp 3\amp -1\amp -2\amp 0
                        \end{array}\right]
                        \xrightarrow{\text{RREF}}
                        \left[\begin{array}{cccc|c}  
                            1\amp 0\amp 1/2\amp 1/2\amp 0\\0\amp 1\amp 1/6\amp -1/6\amp 0
                        \end{array}\right].
                    </me>
                    This shows that <xref ref="linrelationpart1"/> has infinitely many solutions:  
                    <me>
                        c_1=-\frac{1}{2}s-\frac{1}{2}t,\quad c_2=-\frac{1}{6}s+\frac{1}{6}t,\quad c_3=s,\quad c_4=t.
                    </me>
                    Since there are infinitely many solutions, we conclude that the vectors are linearly dependent.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Now to address part <xref ref="item-linindpart2"/> of the remark. 
                    We can use the solution to the homogeneous linear combination equation <xref ref="linrelationpart1"/>
                    to write one of the vectors as a linear combination of the others.
                    Letting <m>t=s=6</m>, we obtain the following:
                    <men xml:id="ex1">
                        -6\begin{bmatrix}2\\-3\end{bmatrix}
                            + 0 \begin{bmatrix}0\\3\end{bmatrix}
                            + 6\begin{bmatrix}1\\-1\end{bmatrix}
                            + 6\begin{bmatrix}1\\-2\end{bmatrix}
                            = \mathbf{0}.
                    </men>
                    Now we solve <xref ref="ex1"/> for one of the vectors: 
                    <men xml:id="ex1lincomb">
                        \begin{bmatrix}2\\-3\end{bmatrix} 
                            = 0\begin{bmatrix}0\\3\end{bmatrix}
                            + \begin{bmatrix}1\\-1\end{bmatrix}
                            + \begin{bmatrix}1\\-2\end{bmatrix}.
                    </men>
                    This would not be possible if a nontrivial solution to the equation
                    <me>
                        c_1\begin{bmatrix}2\\-3\end{bmatrix}
                        + c_2 \begin{bmatrix}0\\3\end{bmatrix}
                        + c_3\begin{bmatrix}1\\-1\end{bmatrix}
                        + c_4\begin{bmatrix}1\\-2\end{bmatrix}
                        = \mathbf{0}
                    </me>
                    did not exist. Therefore, we conclude the answer to both questions in <xref ref="LinIndEquiv"/> is ``YES".
                </p>

                <p>
                    For part <xref ref="item-linindpart2"/> To address linear independence, we need to solve the equation
                    <me>
                        c_1\begin{bmatrix}2\\1\\4\end{bmatrix}+c_2\begin{bmatrix}-3\\1\\1\end{bmatrix}=\mathbf{0}.
                    </me>
                    Converting the equation to augmented matrix form and performing row reduction gives us
                    <me>
                        \left[\begin{array}{cc|c}  
                            2\amp -3\amp 0\\1\amp 1\amp 0\\4\amp 1\amp 0
                        \end{array}\right]
                        \xrightarrow{\text{RREF}}
                        \left[\begin{array}{cc|c}  
                            1\amp 0\amp 0\\0\amp 1\amp 0\\0\amp 0\amp 0
                        \end{array}\right].
                    </me>

                    This shows that <m>c_1=c_2=0</m> is the only solution. 
                    Therefore the two vectors are linearly independent.
                    Furthermore, we cannot write one of the vectors as a linear combination of the other.
                    Do you see that the only way this would be possible with a set of two vectors is if they were scalar multiples of each other?
                </p> 

                <p>
                    So the answer to both questions in <xref ref="LinIndEquiv"/> is ``NO".
                </p>
            </answer>
        </example>


        <theorem xml:id="th-lindeplincombofother">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let <m>\left\{\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots ,\mathbf{v}_k\right\}</m> be a set of vectors in <m>\R^n</m> containing two or more vectors.  The following conditions are equivalent.
                    <ol>
                        <li xml:id="th-lindeplincombofother-a">
                            <p>
                                <m>\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots ,\mathbf{v}_k</m> are linearly dependent.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="th-lindeplincombofother-b">
                            <p>
                                One of <m>\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots ,\mathbf{v}_k</m> can be expressed as a linear combination of the others. 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </theorem>

        <proof>
            <p>
               For <xref ref="th-lindeplincombofother-a"/> <m>\implies</m> <xref ref="th-lindeplincombofother-b"/>,  if <m>\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots ,\mathbf{v}_k</m> are linearly dependent, then
                <me>
                    c_1\mathbf{v}_1+c_2\mathbf{v}_2+\ldots +c_j\mathbf{v}_j+\ldots +c_k\mathbf{v}_k=\mathbf{0}
                </me>
                has a non-trivial solution.  In other words at least one of the constants, say <m>c_j</m>, does not equal zero.  This allows us to solve for <m>\mathbf{v}_j</m>:
                <md>
                    <mrow> 
                        -c_j\mathbf{v}_j
                            \amp = c_1\mathbf{v}_1
                            + c_2\mathbf{v}_2
                            + \ldots 
                            + c_k\mathbf{v}_k 
                    </mrow> 
                    <mrow> 
                        \mathbf{v}_j 
                            \amp = -\frac{c_1}{c_j}\mathbf{v}_1
                            - \frac{c_2}{c_j}\mathbf{v}_2
                            - \ldots 
                            - \frac{c_k}{c_j}\mathbf{v}_k. 
                    </mrow>
                </md>
                Do you see why it was important to have one of the constants nonzero?
                This shows that <m>\mathbf{v}_j</m> may be expressed as a linear combination of the other vectors.
            </p> 

            <p> 
               For the implication <xref ref="th-lindeplincombofother-b"/> <m>\implies</m> <xref ref="th-lindeplincombofother-a"/>, 
               suppose <m>\mathbf{v}_j</m> is a linear combination of <m>\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots,\mathbf{v}_k</m>. 
               We will show that the vectors <m>\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots ,\mathbf{v}_k</m> are linearly dependent.
               That is, there is a non-trivial solution to the homogeneous linear combination equation
               <men xml:id="eq-homoglincomb">
                    x_1\mathbf{v}_1+x_2\mathbf{v}_2+\cdots +x_j\mathbf{v}_j+\cdots +x_k\mathbf{v}_k=\mathbf{0}.
               </men>
               Since <m>\mathbf{v}_j</m> is a linear combination of <m>\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots,\mathbf{v}_k</m>,
               we can write 
               <me>
                    \mathbf{v}_j = a_1\mathbf{v}_1+a_2\mathbf{v}_2+\ldots +a_{j-1}\mathbf{v}_{j-1}+a_{j+1}\mathbf{v}_{j+1}+\ldots +a_k\mathbf{v}_k
               </me>
               for some constants <m>a_1,a_2,\ldots ,a_{j-1},a_{j+1},\ldots ,a_k</m>.
               We can now subtract <m>\mathbf{v}_{j}</m> from both sides of the equation to get:
               <me>
                    a_1\mathbf{v}_1+a_2\mathbf{v}_2+\cdots +a_{j-1}\mathbf{v}_{j-1}-\mathbf{v}_{j}+a_{j+1}\mathbf{v}_{j+1}+\cdots +a_k\mathbf{v}_k
                        = \mathbf{0}
               </me>
               Hence, <m>x_1=a_1, x_2=a_2, \ldots, x_{j-1}=a_{j-1}, x_{j}=-1, x_{j+1}=a_{j+1},\ldots, x_k=a_k</m>
               is a non-trivial solution to the homogeneous linear combination equation <xref ref="eq-homoglincomb"/>.
               This shows that the vectors <m>\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots ,\mathbf{v}_k</m> are linearly dependent.
            </p> 

            <p>
                These two parts of the proof show that if one of the conditions is true, both must be true.
                It is a logical consequence that if one of the conditions is false, both must be false.
            </p>
        </proof>

        Recall that the span of a set of vectors is the set of all linear combinations of those vectors.

        <corollary xml:id="cor-span-of-lin-dependent-vectors">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let <m>X=\left\{\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots ,\mathbf{v}_k\right\}</m> be a set of vectors in <m>\R^n</m>.
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                If <m>X</m> is linearly dependent, then by <xref ref="th-lindeplincombofother"/> there is a vector 
                                <m>\mathbf{v}_j</m> in <m>X</m> that can be written as a linear combination of the other vectors in <m>X</m>
                                and therefore
                                <me>
                                    \text{span}(X)=\text{span}\left(\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\ldots ,\mathbf{v}_{j-1},\mathbf{v}_{j+1},\ldots ,\mathbf{v}_k\right).
                                </me>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                If <m>X</m> is linearly independent, then no vector in <m>X</m> can be written as a linear combination of 
                                the others and hence the span of <m>X</m> cannot be written as the span of a proper subset of <m>\left\{\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots ,\mathbf{v}_k\right\}</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </corollary>
    </subsection>







    <subsection xml:id="Subsection-Geometry-of-Linearly-Dependent-and-Linearly-Independent-Vectors">
        <title>Geometry of Linearly Dependent and Linearly Independent Vectors</title>

        <introduction>
        <p>
            <xref ref="th-lindeplincombofother"/> gives us a convenient way of looking at linear dependence/independence geometrically.  
            When looking at two or more vectors, we ask, <q>Can one of the vectors be written as a linear combination of the others?</q>
            If the answer is <q>YES</q>, then the vectors are linearly dependent.
        </p>
        </introduction>

        <subsubsection xml:id="Subsubsection-A-Set-of-Two-Vectors">
            <title>A Set of Two Vectors</title>

            <p>
                Two vectors are linearly dependent if and only if one is a scalar multiple of the other. 
                Two nonzero linearly dependent vectors may look like this:
            </p>

            <image width="30%">
                <shortdescription> Two vectors that lie on the same line and point in the same direction. </shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                        \draw[line width=1pt,blue,-stealth](0,0)--(2,2);
                        \draw[line width=1pt,red,-stealth](0,0)--(1,1);
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
            
            <p>
                or like this:

            <image width="20%">
                <shortdescription> Two vectors that lie on the same line, but point in opposite directions. </shortdescription>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                            \draw[line width=1pt,blue,-stealth](0,0)--(1,2);
                            \draw[line width=1pt,red,-stealth](0,0)--(-0.5,-1);
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
            </image>
            Either way, the span of the two vectors is a line.
            </p>

            <p>
                Two linearly independent vectors will look like this:
            
            <image width="20%">
                <shortdescription> Two vectors that do not lie on the same line. </shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                        \draw[line width=1pt,blue,-stealth](0,0)--(1,1);
                        \draw[line width=1pt,red,-stealth](0,0)--(0.5,-1);
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>

            and in this case, the span of the two vectors is a plane. 
        </p>
        </subsubsection>


        <subsubsection xml:id="Subsubsection-A-Set-of-Three-Vectors">
            <title>A Set of Three Vectors</title>

            <p>
                Given a set of three nonzero vectors, we have the following possibilities:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        (Linearly Dependent Vectors) The three vectors are scalar multiples of each other.
                    <image width="40%">
                        <shortdescription> Three vectors that lie on the same line. </shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                \draw[line width=1pt,blue,-stealth](0,0)--(2,2);
                                \draw[line width=1pt,red,-stealth](0,0)--(1,1);
                                \draw[line width=1pt,-stealth](0,0)--(0.5,0.5);
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image> 
                    or perhaps one or two of the vectors point in the opposite direction.  
                    In all cases, the span of the three vectors is a line.  
                </p>
                </li>
                   
                <li>
                    <p>
                        (Linearly Dependent Vectors) Two of the vectors are scalar multiples of each other.
                    <image width="40%">
                        <shortdescription> Two vectors that lie on the same line and one that lies on a different line. </shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                \draw[line width=1pt,blue,-stealth](0,0)--(2,2);
                                \draw[line width=1pt,red,-stealth](0,0)--(1,1);
                                \draw[line width=1pt,-stealth](0,0)--(1,0);
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                    and in this case the span of the three vectors is a plane.
                </p>
                </li>
                   
                <li>
                    <p>
                        (Linearly Dependent Vectors) One vector can be viewed as the diagonal of a parallelogram determined by scalar multiples of the other two vectors.
                        All three vectors lie in the same plane.
                    </p>
                    <image width="65%">
                        <shortdescription>
                            Three vectors that lie in the same plane, with one vector being the diagonal of a parallelogram formed by the other two.
                        </shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                \filldraw[blue, opacity=0.3](0,0)--(-2,2)--(2,4)--(4,2)--cycle;
                                \draw[line width=1pt,red,-stealth](0,0)--(2,1);
                                \draw[line width=1pt,red,-stealth, dashed](0,0)--(4,2);
                                \draw[line width=1pt,blue,-stealth](0,0)--(-2,2);
                                \draw[line width=1pt,-stealth](0,0)--(2,4); 
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </li>
                   
                <li>
                    <p>
                        (Linearly Independent Vectors) A set of three vectors is linearly independent if the vectors do not lie in the same plane.
                        For example, the standard basis vectors <m>\mathbf{i}</m>, <m>\mathbf{j}</m> and <m>\mathbf{k}</m> are linearly independent.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </subsubsection>
    </subsection>





